09/25/2023,748.311(10) - Individual Standards Evaluated,Individual Standards Evaluated,No,10/31/2023,10/31/2023,Individual Standards Evaluated,Medium,No,It was determined that the incident report is missing the resolution of the incident. It also does not include any child or adult witnesses. ,"An Email was sent with the following correctives which stated: It was determined that the incident report is missing the resolution of the incident and did not include any child or adult witnesses. 

A Promising Journey (APJ) sets policies and procedures for residents/staff to prevent injury, increase accountability, and avoid unnecessary crisis.

Documentation is also a part of policies and procedures as a method of ensuring that APJ monitors and records all incidents of residents, staff, and that we are using best practices.  
After an incident is managed (staff being in arms reach as well as in close sight), a critical report will be completed for the resident and stored in her file. Documentation of the event will be kept in the residents file. Information within the report will include: 
1.	Type of incident
2.	Date and time of the incident
3.	Supervisor contacted, including method of contact, and time of contact.
4.	Local authorities contacted and the time of contact (if applicable).
5.	Case worker contacted, time and method of contact.
6.	Hotline called, time of call and incident number given (if applicable).
7.	Documentation of the incident location, when completed.
8.	End result/resolution; and
9.	Witnesses (child and/or adult)

"
09/09/2023,748.2203(a) - Individual Standards Evaluated,Individual Standards Evaluated,No,11/10/2023,10/31/2023,Individual Standards Evaluated,Medium High,Yes,No contact with a health care professional was made when the child was given the wrong medication.,"An email was sent with the following correctives: When a medication administration error occurs, staff will follow these guidelines:
1.	keep the resident in the room where medication was dispensed.
2.	If the resident has already returned to her room, have someone accompany the resident back to the area where dispensed.      
3.	observe the residents status and document what you see.      
4.	identify the incorrect dose or type of medication taken by the resident.     
5.	notify the case manager and supervising staff immediately if medication was given by non-licensed personnel (The supervising staff will contact the LCCA, Executive Director, and/or health care provider of the resident.)      
6.	if contacting the Poison Control Center for instructions: 
a.	give the name and dose of the medication taken in error.         
b.	give the residents age and approximate weight, if possible        
c.	give the name and dose of any other medication the resident receives, if possible 
7.	follow instructions from the Poison Control Center, if possible.  If unable to follow their instructions, explain the problem to the Poison Control Center to determine if the resident should be transported for emergency care. 
8.	Notify the residents health-care provider via telephone, document, follow up with an email, and adhere to the given instructions/recommendations.
9.	complete the Critical Incident Report form. Carefully record all circumstances and actions taken, including instructions from the Poison Control Center and/or the residents health care provider, and the residents status.  All reports are to be filed and kept according to A Promising Journey Inc.s policy.   
 
Lastly, errors made in recording medications on the Medication Administration Record should be marked void/error initialed and dated. Whiteout may not be used.  Medical errors may lead to fines, corrective action and/or a finding of abuse.






